   117→ * for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
   118→ *     producer.send(new ProducerRecord<String, String>("my-topic", Integer.toString(i), Integer.toString(i)));
   119→ *
   120→ * producer.close();
   121→ * }</pre>
   122→ * <p>
   123→ * The producer consists of a pool of buffer space that holds records that haven't yet been transmitted to the server
   124→ * as well as a background I/O thread that is responsible for turning these records into requests and transmitting them
   125→ * to the cluster. Failure to close the producer after use will leak these resources.
   126→ * <p>
   127→ * The {@link #send(ProducerRecord) send()} method is asynchronous. When called, it adds the record to a buffer of pending record sends
   128→ * and immediately returns. This allows the producer to batch together individual records for efficiency.
   129→ * <p>
   130→ * The <code>acks</code> config controls the criteria under which requests are considered complete. The default setting "all"
   131→ * will result in blocking on the full commit of the record, the slowest but most durable setting.
   132→ * <p>
   133→ * If the request fails, the producer can automatically retry. The <code>retries</code> setting defaults to <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>, and
   134→ * it's recommended to use <code>delivery.timeout.ms</code> to control retry behavior, instead of <code>retries</code>.
   135→ * <p>
   136→ * The producer maintains buffers of unsent records for each partition. These buffers are of a size specified by
   137→ * the <code>batch.size</code> config. Making this larger can result in more batching, but requires more memory (since we will
   138→ * generally have one of these buffers for each active partition).
   139→ * <p>
   140→ * By default a buffer is available to send immediately even if there is additional unused space in the buffer. However if you
   141→ * want to reduce the number of requests you can set <code>linger.ms</code> to something greater than 0. This will
   142→ * instruct the producer to wait up to that number of milliseconds before sending a request in hope that more records will
   143→ * arrive to fill up the same batch. This is analogous to Nagle's algorithm in TCP. For example, in the code snippet above,
